15358,Innocence Lost: First Bull Run 1861,"['Dice Rolling', 'Hexagon Grid', 'Simulation']","['American Civil War', 'Civil War', 'Print & Play', 'Wargame']","Innocence Lost: First Bull Run 1861 is a Desk-Top-Publishing Tactical level board-wargame on the first major engagement of the American Civil  War war....excellent counters and even better map: typical DTP fare 2-part map and cut out counters but worth the price unlike at a lot of games out there.<br/><br/>For all the students of the ACW here is another variation on the first great battle of the War, First Manassas. Using a system derived from Ivy Street&rsquo;s brigade level wargames, but with a totally different combat method, Innocence Lost uses a chit drawing activation system, that strains the command differences between the two rival armies in this early stages of the Civil  War. With historical and what-if scenarios and variants.<br/><br/>It is a fast and furious wargame, easily playable both face-to-face than solitaire in under 2 hours.<br/>4 A4 full color maps and 140 full-color counters with the usual impressing graphics that gained a nomination for best DTP effort at 2003 Charles Robert Awards<br/><br/>Released as Print-n-Play in June 2007. Available as a DTP game from Boulder Games.<br/><br/>",2002,,,
15359,Game of Football,"['Dice Rolling', 'Simulation']",['Sports'],"This game, simulating the American gridiron version of football, comes with a game board representing a football field, a football pin, two pins with colored heads to be used as a 10 yard marker, a dice cup and two dice. As in real football the object is to advance the ball over the opponents goal line for a score. Dice rolls are used for all aspects of the game. The kickoff, for example, travels a distance equal to 5 times the throw of the dice. The receiving player then rolls the dice for the return; if it's an even number, the ball is brought back the number of yards rolled, but if it's an odd number no gain is made. The offense may choose either a Line Plunge, an End Run, a Forward Pass, or a Trick Play. The greater a play's potential for gain, the greater risk of no gain or a loss of yards. A roll of doubles results in either a penalty or a turnover. When the time limit agreed upon by the players (before the game) is reached, the player who has the highest total score is the winner.<br/><br/>",1948,,,
