16335,Satellite Space Race Card Game,['Open Drafting'],"['Card Game', ""Children's Game"", 'Science Fiction', 'Space Exploration']","Space Race is a simple card game designed for two players, though more can play with additional card sets (as there is no player interaction whatsoever).<br/><br/>The object of the game is to complete a round trip through the Solar System by drawing ten planet cards in their proper order. (The order will be unfamiliar, though, as it goes Earth -&gt; Saturn -&gt; Jupiter -&gt; Mars -&gt; Uranus -&gt; Neptune -&gt; Venus -&gt; Mercury -&gt; Earth). Each card features well executed art done in a style similar to golden age science fiction pulp magazines.<br/><br/>The game consists of two identical decks with cards numbered 1-10. These cards represent round trips the the Solar System, starting with &quot;Take Off&quot; (Card 1) and ending with &quot;Landing On Earth&quot; (Card 10). Players take a deck and shuffle it, then place it before them. The first player draws a card. If it is &quot;Take Off&quot; (Card 1), they place it in front of them and draw the next card. If the next card is a planet but not Card 2, they discard it in a discard pile next to their original pile and draw again, until they draw a card that says &quot;Next player goes&quot;. The next player takes a turn, and draws until they get a &quot;Next player goes&quot; card. Chance cards such as &quot;lost on the moon,&quot; &quot;Sputnik,&quot; and &quot;Danger--Comets&quot; can affect a player's turn.<br/><br/>Players may draw from either pile, so there is a memory element, as you must remember which pile your next planetary target was in.<br/><br/>All cards must be discarded in the pile next to the pile from which they were drawn.<br/><br/>The goal is to collect all 10 cards, in sequence.<br/><br/>Rules list a variant for three or more players through using multiple copies of the game.<br/><br/>",1952,,,
