16788,Der kleine Schlaumeier,['Dice Rolling'],"['Dice', 'Word Game']","The goal is to advance your figure to the end of a 10 space track first. The board has a spinner in the middle with 22 yellow spaces showing a letter and a number, 4 red spaces showing a sad or angry face and a number and 2 green spaces showing a happy face. On a players turn he spins the spinner. If it stops on a letter he takes a card and reads out the category on it (eg &quot;profession&quot; or &quot;funny birthday present&quot;). The neighbor to his right has to say a word that starts with the given letter and fits the category in 10 seconds, if he does so he may advance 1 space on his track. The other players still have the chance to advance 1 space by rolling the number on the letter space of the spinner. If the spinner stops on a red space all players have to roll the die and go back 1 space if they roll the number on the spinner's space. If the spinner stops on a green space the player who spun may advance 2 spaces.<br/><br/>",0,,,
16789,Legepladsen,[],"['Educational', 'Math']","Legepladsen is a game for children. Each child has a Lego-figure which has to collect 3 pieces of Lego each. The game can be played in 3 different ways depending on the age of the child. There are 3 different piles of cards, depending on which variation you choose. With the youngest children you simply have to draw a card and then move the same number as shown on the card. With older children you can choose either to play with addition or subtraction. To move on the board you have to draw 2 cards and move the sum of the cards. When you pass the symbol with the piece of Lego you can take one. The winner is the first player to collect 3 pieces of Lego and then get back to start. There are 2 tiles which can be placed on the board: Either you can have an extra turn or you miss your turn. Playing the game children can learn to count and calculate as well as game-mechanics as turn-taking, drawing cards, taking extra turns and missing a turn.<br/><br/>",0,,,
16790,Best Sellers,['Storytelling'],['Word Game'],"The 52 cards each feature a picture of a book cover on one side and a letter on the reverse side. The book covers have titles and illustrations the relate to specific themes. Each letter of the alphabet appears twice within the deck and five of those letters (J,Q,X,Y,Z) are yellow, indicating a higher value for those letters.<br/><br/>Each game of Best Sellers consists of ten rounds. During each round, one player is designated as EDITOR. The editor shuffles the deck and presents them to the player on his left. The player draws three cards, flipping over two of them to reveal the letters on the backs. The book title on the third card is the theme to be used for the round.<br/><br/>Once the book title and the two letters have been chosen, the editor starts the two minute timer and all players, including the editor, begin writing a story inspired by the title/theme of the book cover. Players earn points by including as many words as possible which begin with either of the two letters chosen for the round. Each word that begins with one of these letters is worth one point.<br/><br/>- Words only count the first time they are used.<br/>- Words must be in complete sentences to count.<br/>- Words beginning with yellow letters are worth 2 points.<br/><br/>When the two minutes are up, each player stops writing. Beginning with the player immediately to the editor's left, each participant reads his/her story and announces the number of points earned. The editor adds the totals to the score sheet for the round and awards the book card to the player with the most points. At the end of ten rounds, players total their scores from each round, add 3 points for every book card held to reach a grand total. The player with the most points at the end of ten rounds is the winner of the game.<br/><br/>",2002,,,
