16885,Big Time Baseball,"['Dice Rolling', 'Point to Point Movement']",['Sports'],"Big League Baseball bills itself as &quot;The World Series of Baseball Games.&quot; It uses a curious dice-rolling mechanism that allows players to try to place their fly balls, ground balls, and bunts on a spot of the field least covered by opposing fielders. Strategy comes into play on offense in strategically allocating dice for a fly ball; on defense with positioning fielders to optimally cover the field.<br/><br/>No production date is given, but one of the Sid Sackson collection copies of this game was marked as being acquired in 1983.<br/><br/>",1983,,,
16886,Baseball's Greatest Moments,['Roll / Spin and Move'],"['Sports', 'Trivia']","Baseball's Greatest Moments is a game in which each player's knowledge of baseball trivia is put to the test. Two to six players buy &quot;souvenirs&quot; and &quot;baseball memorabilia&quot; with the answer points awarded for correct answers. The winner must acquire 1500 points in souvenirs/memorabilia, 100 points in answer points, and answer a final challenge question in the last zone of the game board.<br/><br/>",1979,,,
16887,Capital Hill,"['Hand Management', 'Open Drafting', 'Roll / Spin and Move']","['Economic', 'Political']","&quot;Capital Hill&quot;, as the title suggests, is a game of accumulating money through the political process. In the regular version, three to six players start with a randomly determined number of chips representing Senators and members of the House of Representatives. Each player directs their politicians to gain power and money by winning elections, holding onto power positions, and passing laws. Players are eliminated when they lose all their representation in the House and Senate. When only two players remain, the player with the most money is declared the winner.<br/><br/>A short version permits two to six players to compete for a fixed number of game rounds; again, the player with the most money at the end is the winner.<br/><br/>",1991,,,
16888,Coloption,"['Point to Point Movement', 'Roll / Spin and Move']","['Abstract Strategy', 'Dice']","&quot;Coloption&quot; is also known as &quot;Col*ption&quot;.<br/><br/>From the rules:<br/><br/>&quot;COLOPTION is a fast paced adult game with some gaming elements familiar to generations of games players and new devices [...]. The object of the game, which is played on a geometrically designed game board, is to move your men from their home base to a goal. To do this, you must roll combinations of dice and color cubes and move your men through an exit triangle, hazard hexagon, safety zones, alien colors and goal paths. If that's not enough, there's also the danger of being 'bumped' by other players!<br/><br/>&quot;COLOPTION can be played by two to six players which immediately makes it more sociable than backgammon which is played as a twosome. A round is over when all of one player's men have either reached the goal or been bumped. A round usually lasts from fifteen to thirty minutes. Play can be for several rounds as in backgammon or for point totals as in bridge.&quot;<br/><br/>",1978,,,
16889,Conservation,['Roll / Spin and Move'],['Transportation'],"In &quot;Conservation&quot;, players move their cars along the board's outer track, then the inner track, and then to their service station in the middle. Along the way, they face state fines and maintenance issues for their car. The game ends when a player reaches their service station, but the winner is the player with the most money at the end.<br/><br/>",1980,,,
16890,Containment,"['Dice Rolling', 'Roll / Spin and Move']",['Environmental'],"&quot;Containment&quot; is a game played between pro-nuclear and anti-nuclear factions. Pro-nuclear players try to go &quot;on line&quot; and produce electricity; anti-nuclear players try to shut down the reactor and switch to alternate forms of energy production. A reactor in the center of the board moves either towards or away from meltdown as the game progresses, depending on the players' actions.<br/><br/>&quot;Containment&quot; may be played on three levels: a Basic game that is purely luck driven, a Standard game that uses arguments and counterarguments (given on the game board) in the nuclear power debate to influence game play, and an Advanced game that calls on the players to evaluate and rank their own arguments as well as those of their opponents.<br/><br/>The game is obviously inspired by the events at the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant in 1979, as one of the arguments given on the game board explicitly mentions TMI. The box cover artwork is also very evocative of TMI.<br/><br/>",1979,,,
16891,Corvette,"['Hand Management', 'Open Drafting', 'Roll / Spin and Move']",['Transportation'],"&quot;Corvette&quot; bills itself as &quot;the automobile maintenance and trading game.&quot; However, it somehow feels more like a Chevy advertising piece, as each player progresses from owning a Cavalier through a Celebrity, Caprice, and Camaro in their quest to be the first to own a Corvette and be free of debt.<br/><br/>2-6 players compete in an admittedly simplistic game: collect money by passing &quot;payday&quot;, then hope to avoid spending it all on car maintenance in order to buy a better car. Judicious selection of which &quot;pick up&quot; cards (coupons and special board advance cards) to keep in one's hand add a little strategy to an otherwise &quot;roll and move&quot; style game.<br/><br/>",1985,,,
16892,Counter All Terrorists!,['Trick-taking'],"['Card Game', 'Spies/Secret Agents']","&quot;Counter All Terrorists&quot; challenges its players to defend against a series of terrorist attacks on the United States. The game may be played solitaire, or by up to six players. As the title suggests, the object is to counter terrorists' attacks on the &quot;White House, Pentagon, CIA, FBI, Air Force One, and many military bases and cities across the United States.&quot;<br/><br/>It is an unusual title in terms of historical insight, having been published in 1986 and embellishing its instructions with Albert Einstein's quote, &quot;imagination is more important than knowledge.&quot; The game treats a subject that few would take seriously at the time -- though, in hindsight, its designers also failed in imagination for the weights given the various terror targets.<br/><br/>",1986,,,
