 cards and acquiring levels. Being defeated by a monster results in &quot;bad stuff&quot; which usually involves losing levels and treasure.<br/><br/>",2005,,,
16934,Captain Kidd's Treasure,['Point to Point Movement'],['Pirates'],"The object of the game is to move your ship from one Treasure corner of the board to any other Treasure corner. Instead of using a die to dictate movement, the game uses a shuttered Light House &quot;spinner&quot;. Players rotate the light house wheel in either direction until a dot appears. Opening the shutter at this point reveals a &quot;light&quot; that tells how many spaces the ship may move.<br/><br/>Some strategy comes into play, as circle spaces at the board's pathway intersections confer both advantages and disadvantages. A ship on a circle space *must* turn left or right on its next turn, but a player whose ship on a circle may move another player's ship if that move will put his opponent on a circle space.<br/><br/>",1927,,,
