18363,Keep On Truckin' America,['Roll / Spin and Move'],['Transportation'],"Players complete trips across the united states as truckers. The game includes an oversized gameboard, money, various types of special cards (Dispatch Cards, Smokey Sez! Cards, Bonus Cards, Truck Scales Cards, Keep On Truckin' Cafe Cards, and Time Cards), and small plastic trucks.<br/><br/>The game begins by rolling for a dispatch card. Then players roll the die and move along their assigned route (from the dispatch card). Many spaces require that a user draw a card and follow the directions. Once a player finishes five trips he wins.<br/><br/>The game is an attempt to present a realistic trucking experience. For instance (quote from the rules): &quot;If a trucker cannot pay a debt or loses all of his money, he is bankrupt. Going bankrupt is one of the realities of trucking. The player cannot borrow money. He cannot continue to play.&quot;<br/><br/>",1976,,,
18364,Top Gear: The Game,[],"['Card Game', 'Movies / TV / Radio theme', 'Transportation', 'Trivia']","&quot;From Alfa to Austin, from Zodiac to Zasgato, how much do you really know about cars?  Well more than cars actually!  If you want to hold your head up high in the car park again, you are going to have to know a lot about all aspects of motoring including motor sport, the Highway Code, and a whole lot of useless trivia.  Why will this be important to you?  Well to win the game of course.  Oh, but much more than that, much more.  Your whole reputation and street credibility could be at stake, because at the end of the game, your score will be analyzed, your personality checked, and you will find out what car really does suit you!&quot;<br/><br/>TOP GEAR - THE GAME is a motoring trivia game themed to the BBC TV series of the same name.  Players take it in turns to spin a spinner and answer questions (from one of six different packs) as indicated.  The answer given will result in a tick or a cross being recorded on the individual's scoresheet against one of four personality categories - looks, performance, running cost, safety.<br/><br/>If the spinner points at the figure '9' rather than a question category then a marker is moved along a scale at the bottom of the spinner card.  The game ends when a total of 9 '9's have been spun.<br/><br/>The winner is the person with the most ticks on their score card.  In the event of a draw the person with the least crosses is the winner.<br/><br/>Once a winner has been declared all player can then look up their &quot;ideal&quot; car in the reference book provided with the rules.  This is done simply by totaling up all the answers provided in each personality category (correct and incorrect) and placing the categories in order.  The relative order of the personality traits will indicate whether you should be driving a McLaren F1 or a Sinclair C5.<br/><br/>",1993,,,
18365,Word-Power,['Roll / Spin and Move'],"['Educational', 'Party Game', 'Trivia', 'Word Game']","WORD-POWER is a boardgame concerned with vocabulary, and in particular the definitions of English words.  The aim of the game is to progress around the board which represents attendance at Primary School, High School, College and University, collecting points through correctly answering questions.  In order to graduate you must pass through the finish square with 300 or more points.<br/><br/>Movement around the board is determined by a dice roll, though players are able to select the route they take.  Landing on a colored square will require players to answer 1, 2 or 3 questions from a given category (blue - easy, green - moderate, red - difficult). The questions are concerned with providing a definition of a given word - if this can be done without any assistance 10 points are awarded - if however the player elects to be given three options from the card only 5 points are awarded for a correct answer.<br/><br/>Points gained are recorded on a notepad with players being able to progress from one educational institution to the next having earned the requisite number of points:<br/>50 to leave primary School<br/>100 to leave High School<br/>200 to leave College.<br/><br/>The first player to reach the finish with more than 300 points is the winner.<br/><br/>",1990,,,
18366,Take A Taxi,['Roll / Spin and Move'],['Transportation'],"Take a Taxi is a game of luck and strategy, but mostly luck. Each player &quot;owns&quot; passengers and runs a taxi. The goal is to pick up as many of the other player's passengers as possible, delivering them to their destinations, collecting money and avoiding fines.<br/><br/>All players begin with $150.00 and 4 Passenger Pawns (same color as their taxi). Players distribute their Passenger Pawns on the board, as well as Bank owned Pawns and Police/Highway Patrol Cars.<br/><br/>The object is to pick up as many of the other players&rsquo; pawns as possible and deliver them to their destination (as determined by the draw from the card deck).  Taxi drivers collect $1/space driven from the owning player of the pawn, but the route must be direct because cheating gets you a $20.00 fine and a trip back to the garage.  The Bank pays for Bank Pawns. Whenever a Passenger Pawn is picked up, a Destination Card is drawn, but beware the random Hazard Card!<br/><br/>Police/Highway Patrol Cars are moved by the current player who rolls either a &lsquo;1&rsquo; or a &lsquo;6&rsquo;. The object is to &ldquo;Bust&rdquo; one of the other taxis caught in its jurisdiction (spaces marked yellow on the board). When a player has picked all the pawns he can, they head back to the garage to end the game. The person with the most money wins the game. Bank Pawns in possession are worth $5.00 each.<br/><br/>The length of the game is dependent on the amount of players. Placement of the Bank Pawns also adds to the game length, since players can choose to keep a Bank Pawn, or put it into play:  more pawns in play equals a longer game.<br/><br/>",1991,,,
