18697,Think Twice,"['Paper-and-Pencil', 'Pattern Building', 'Square Grid']",['Abstract Strategy'],"Think Twice is played on two 6x6 grids each filled with the numbers 1-36 - each player fills one grid as they wish before the game starts.<br/><br/>On a turn a player selects one of the numbers and fills in the corresponding space on each grid. This continues until all the spaces are filled.<br/><br/>Players score for lines of four, five, and six in any direction. In addition, bonus points are awarded on each grid for the player with the largest connected group of spaces: they score the difference in size between this and the other player's largest group on that grid.<br/><br/>",1986,,,
18698,Archimedes,"['Point to Point Movement', 'Square Grid']",['Abstract Strategy'],"Archimedes is a nautical battle game for 2 players.<br/><br/>The board is an 8&times;8 grid, and each player has 10 (in the original version) or 12 &quot;ships&quot; represented by pieces of one color. The object of the game is to capture the opponent's ships.<br/><br/>Pieces may move any distance in any direction. They do not capture by moving; instead, a piece that could move to an opposing piece's space threatens it, and a piece threatened by at least three pieces may be captured.<br/><br/>A captured piece may be placed on the board as one's own piece instead of moving a piece. (The pieces need to be reversible or extra pieces need to be available to swap for.)<br/><br/>Online Play<br/><br/><br/>    Super Duper Games<br/><br/><br/>",1975,,,
18699,EinStein würfelt nicht!,"['Dice Rolling', 'Roll / Spin and Move']",['Abstract Strategy'],"EinStein w&uuml;rfelt nicht! is the official game accompanying an German exhibition about Einstein in the Einstein Year 2005. It's a fast paced game for 2 players.<br/><br/>The game board is 5&times;5 square fields large.<br/><br/>Each player controls 6 playing pieces i.e. stones with the numbers 1 to 6 marked on them.<br/><br/>The stones of player 1 are set up in the six fields of the upper left corner of the board and those of player 2 in the six fields of the lower right corner of the board so they face each other diagonally.<br/><br/>During his turn a player rolls a die, if he still has the stone with the number corresponding to the rolled value on the board he must move this stone. If the corresponding stone was already removed from play (see below) the player may choose to either move the stone with the next higher or the next lower number.<br/><br/>In his move player 1 may move the stone one field to the right, downward or diagonally to the lower right. Respectively player 2 may move the stone one field to the left, upward or diagonally to the upper left.<br/><br/>If a player ends his move on a field occupied by another stone, be it one of the opponent or one of his own stones, then this stone is removed from play.<br/><br/>To win the game a player must occupy the corner field of the opponent with a playing piece.  A player loses if he has no more playing pieces left on the board.<br/><br/>",2004,,,
