19461,Gambling Games of Malaya,"['Betting and Bluffing', 'Dice Rolling']","['Bluffing', 'Book', 'Card Game', 'Dice']","This book was written by an Assistant Commissioner of Police as an aid for Magistrates in Malayan Courts who had to hear cases involving all manner of gambling games common in the region at the time.<br/><br/>As the author, Dobree, says in his preface to the book, dated 1st February 1955, &quot;The book contains detailed descriptions of the majority of gambling games, betting and lottery games and betting which usually form or which may form subjects of charges in this country under the Common Gaming Houses Ordinance No. 26/1953 and the Betting Ordinance No. 47/1953.<br/><br/>Also mentioned for the most part briefly, are other popular gambling games mostly in the card game category, which do not usually form subjects of criminal charges as they are invariably played under circumstances which do not constitute any offense under the Ordinance ...&quot;<br/><br/>Although intended to be a functional legal document, this book has concurrently become a major reference work for gambling games in South-East Asia, containing descriptions and rules for games not described in English in print elsewhere. Dice and playing card collectors will find this volume to be an indispensable repository of information on rare and unusual Asian specimens. The work is liberally illustrated with colour plates of gambling implements.<br/><br/>A list of the contents follows:<br/><br/>Foreword<br/>Preface<br/>Notes on Legal Aspects of the Ordinances<br/>Definitions<br/>DOCUMENTARY BETTING AND LOTTERY GAMES:<br/> An Introductory Note to the Games of Chee Fah or Hwah Hwey, Chee Tam and Chap Ji Kee<br/> Chee Fah, Hwah Hwey or 36 Numbers<br/> Whay - Kelantan version of Chee Fah<br/> Chee Tam or 80 Characters<br/> Chap Ji Kee<br/> Sap Sam Tai Poh<br/> Wee Sua Peow or Wei San Piew,or Tong Sua Peow or Quay Suay Peow<br/> Pak Kap Piew or Pigeon Lottery<br/> Tikam Ekor or 100, 1,000 and 10,000 Number Games<br/> Lucky Numbers at &quot;Fun&quot; and Similar Fairs<br/>GAMES WITH CARDS:<br/> Games with English Cards<br/> Games with Chinese Cards<br/>  - Soo Sik Pai<br/>  - Luk Foo Pai<br/>  - Seong Kum Pai or Pin Kum Pai<br/>  - Chi Kee Pai<br/>  - Sap Ng Hor Pai<br/>  - Tung Koon Pai<br/>  - Oh Peh Pai<br/> Pair<br/> Sap Sam Cheong or Lushun Poker<br/> Three Cards, Sam Cheong, Pa Kau or Daun Tiga<br/> Koo Kiew, Ten Kiew or Soo Kiew<br/> Tau Ngau<br/> Twenty One<br/> Thirty One<br/> Ten and a Half<br/> Minta Daun<br/> Three Card Trick, Mai Wong or Tikam Raja<br/>GAMES WITH DOMINOES:<br/> Pai Kow<br/> Tau Ngau<br/> Tien Kow<br/>DICE GAMES:<br/> Yew, Yee, Sam or One, Two, Three<br/> Tai Sai or Big and Small (Simple Form) <br/> Luk Kow or Dicing Six<br/> Sepat<br/> Ta Kai or Cockfighting<br/> Chong Yuen Chow<br/> Sek Poh<br/> Sek Chai Tan or Kok Kok<br/> Tai Sai or Big and Small - using Staking Board<br/> Tai Sai combined with Sek Chai Tan<br/> Hoo, Hey, How<br/>MISCELLANEOUS GAMES:<br/> Chap Ji Kee Pangjang<br/> Daun Empat or See Kee Yah<br/> Fan Tan or Tuahn<br/> Four Numbers<br/> Poh, Lien Poh or Ewok<br/> Staking Methods in Fan Tan, Poh, Four Numbers and Sek Chai Tan<br/> Pek Bin<br/> Belankai<br/> Dadu Katak Ular (a Javanese Game)<br/> Dadu Muka Enam (a Javanese Game)<br/> Dadu Belankas Mata (a Boyanese Game)<br/> 136 Numbers<br/> Solhi (a Punjabi Game)<br/> Games with Mah Jong Tiles<br/> Games in Amusement Parks<br/> Fruit Machines<br/> Horse Race Betting and Bookmakers<br/><br/>N.B. Page numbers and Chinese characters have been omitted from the listing of the contents.<br/><br/>",1955,,,
19462,Hor Lor Boon,"['Dice Rolling', 'Roll / Spin and Move']","['Dice', 'Racing']","The name of this traditional roll-and-move race game possibly derives from the hulu (Mandarin) or hor lor (Hokkien dialect), which means a gourd, that often appears as a symbol on the board. In the catalogue for the exhibition, Asian Games: The Art of Contest, the following names for this game are mentioned:<br/>hulu pan (gourd board) - southern Fujian and eastern Guangdong area<br/>hulu qi (gourd chess) in Hong Kong<br/>hulu wen (gourd puzzle)in Suzhou<br/>fenghuang qi (male and female phoenix chess)in places such as Tianjin, Weixian (Shandong Province), and Chengdu (Sichuan Province).<br/><br/>I know it, in Singapore, as Hor Lor Boon.<br/><br/>This game is played on a board showing a spiral track and the object is to move one's piece from the outside into the center of the track first(q.v. Game of Goose and Sheng Guan Tu). The track is made up of individual symbols which will be repeated once on the board. Players roll two dice and move the number of symbols along the track. Wherever they land, they will then jump to the corresponding symbol elsewhere on the board (which could be a help or a hindrance). It's not necessary to land exactly on the center square to win - passing it also wins.<br/><br/>The symbols may vary, but are usually traditional or mythological Chinese figures (e.g. the Eight Immortals, creatures from the Chinese zodiac) and would include a gourd (hor lor).<br/><br/>A contemporary set made in China called cai shen you xi qi (God of fortune game) has two pieces for each player - presumably the roll can only apply to one of the pieces in this version (the rules are not clear on this). The rules for this version state that if a piece is supposed to land on a space occupied by another piece, it remains where it is and the piece it would have landed on is sent back to the start. The board features the God of Fortune as the central space that all the players are trying to reach.<br/><br/>",0,,,
