19496,SARS War,['Roll / Spin and Move'],['Educational'],"SARS Wars &ndash; Sha Si Zhan Qi<br/><br/>Towards the end of the SARS (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome) outbreak in Singapore in 2003, an enterprising media company published this simple roll-and-move board game, incorporating the public health education messages that were issued at the time. It was sold at branches of a book-cum-stationery shop chain, Popular Bookstore.<br/><br/>The game is for 2 to 6 players and players each have a coloured pawn that moves along a spiral track towards an End Point. Along the way, players follow instructions on spaces they land on, including taking two kinds of chance cards.<br/><br/>The &lsquo;Personal Hygiene&rsquo; card is drawn when landing on a &lsquo;Personal Hygiene&rsquo; square &ndash; players follow whatever instructions are written on these cards. The &lsquo;See Doctor&rsquo; cards may be drawn when landing on a &lsquo;Symptoms&rsquo; square, or also after landing on a &lsquo;Check Your Temperature&rsquo; square and rolling a 4, 5, or 6 (on lower numbers your temperature is normal, so you naturally don&rsquo;t need to see a doctor).<br/><br/>Players may also get sent to Hospital or be put under Home Quarantine. Being in the Hospital is worse as the player proceeds to Home Quarantine after discharge from hospital.<br/><br/>The game has lots of humorous touches that reflect the atmosphere at the time. One of the pre-game preparation rules is, &ldquo;All players must wash their hands thoroughly before playing&rdquo;. There&rsquo;s also a rule concerning expulsion from the game, &ldquo;You are not allowed to continue with the game when you are expelled because of reckless, irresponsible personal misconduct that jeopardizes the entire community&rdquo;.<br/><br/>The first player to reach the End Point is the &lsquo;overall winner&rsquo; of the game. The other players can continue to play the game. Ominously, &ldquo;the last player left is the loser, who may be punished appropriately&rdquo;.<br/><br/>",2003,,,
