19969,Truc,"['Betting and Bluffing', 'Hand Management', 'Team-Based Game', 'Trick-taking']","['Bluffing', 'Card Game', 'Party Game']","Truco is widely played in South America. It is derived from the simpler game Truc, which is played in Valencia, Balearic Islands and parts of Italy. Each player is dealt three cards, which are played out in tricks, and points are also scored for holding combinations of cards in the same suit. It is the possible to bet extra points on who has the best combination or will win the tricks, and the bluffing, talking and joking that goes with this are an important part of the game. Truco is usually played by four players in partnerships, but it can also be played by two or six.<br/><br/>(Taken from the website <a target='_blank' href=""http://www.pagat.com/put/truc.html"" rel=""nofollow noreferrer noopener"">http://www.pagat.com/put/truc.html</a> )<br/><br/>",0,,,
19970,Force Intriguing Games,['Roll / Spin and Move'],"['Modern Warfare', 'Racing']","This is a made-in-China variant of ludo in which players get 3 pieces and have to get them from their base to the central spot. <br/>The number of spaces to move is much less than in ludo and there are spaces that might move the player's pieces forwards or backwards. Fairly nasty is the space on the home stretch that forces the piece to move backwards into the path of other pieces. <br/>The game has a military theme and pieces are toy soldiers in different colours. I would guess that while each colour has 3 soldiers, the poses you get might vary from box to box.<br/><br/>",0,,,
19971,Toepen,"['Betting and Bluffing', 'Trick-taking']","['Bluffing', 'Card Game']","Tuppen is a popular trick-taking game in parts of Germany and the Nethelands (Limburg and Noord Brabant). It is played with a 32-card deck, the order of cards being J (low),Q ,K ,A ,7 ,8 ,9 ,10 (high). Each hand consists of four tricks, players must follow suit if able and the player who takes the last trick wins. Players accumulate points whenever they lose a hand, and are eliminated at seven points. Dice are commonly used to keep track of the score. The initial value of each hand is one point. It can be &quot;knocked&quot; (raised) by one point at any time by any player, except that no player may knock twice in a row. Players can either accept a raise or fold and take the lower number of points. Upon reaching six points a player is in &quot;poverty&quot; and subsequent hands are worth at least two points.<br/><br/>",0,,,
19972,Lernen Sie Die A-Klasse Kennen,"['Solo / Solitaire Game', 'Stacking and Balancing']",['Puzzle'],"Not an easy solo game! The point is that a team of 4 members has to build the A-Class in exactly 60 time units. 6 components (the puzzle pieces) have to be brought from &ldquo;B&rdquo; to &ldquo;A&rdquo;. The team members need different lengths of time from &ldquo;A&rdquo; to &ldquo;B&rdquo;: 25, 20, 10 and 5 time units. The journey back from &ldquo;A&rdquo; to &ldquo;B&rdquo; takes the same amount of time. Two team members always have to go from &ldquo;A&rdquo; to &ldquo;B&rdquo; together. This costs the higher of the two time units. Each member is allowed to take one component with them. One of the two has to go back to &ldquo;B&rdquo;. The task is solved if all 6 components are brought from &ldquo;B&rdquo; to &ldquo;A&rdquo; in exactly 60 time units in this way. To measure time, use the timeline on the game board with the staff as a timer. Since the task is not easy to solve, there are two tips under the cardboard insert and - if these are still not enough - a complete solution.<br/><br/>A challenging puzzle for one person that is sure to cause some headaches if you can resist the temptation to read the tips and solution. A very attractive advertising game that is sure to enrich the collection of any lover of brain teasers!<br/><br/>",0,,,
